# Folder Structure & Styling

## Top-level layout

- **`settings.ts`** — App settings and validated environment variables. Uses a Zod schema to parse `import.meta.env` at startup and exports a typed `settings` object. All code reads env vars from `settings` — never from `import.meta.env` directly.
- **`generated/`** — **Auto-generated** by `@hey-api/openapi-ts` from `openapi.json`. Contains typed SDK functions, Zod schemas, TanStack Query options, and the Axios client. **Never edit manually** — regenerate with `npm run openapi-ts`. Gitignored.
- **`routes/`** — Route definitions and route-level components (e.g. root layout, index).
- **`features/`** — Feature-based modules. Each feature (and sub-features) lives here.
- **`utils/`** — Shared utilities; same level as `features/`.
- **`infra/`** — Shared integrations (not `lib`): clients (TanStack, Stripe, HTTP), **services** (adapters that wrap those clients), and `hey-api.config.ts` (runtime config for the generated client).
- **`errors/`** — Custom error classes (e.g. `errors.ts` or `errors/errors.ts`). Used by services and caught by the global error boundary.
- **`theme/`** — `theme.ts` plus `theme/components/` for shared UI components.

## Feature structure

Each feature (and sub-feature) uses this layout:

```
features/
  auth/
    components/   # Feature-specific components
    hooks/       # Feature-specific hooks
    page/        # The actual page(s)
    service/     # Feature-specific service/API
  dashboard/
    components/
    hooks/
    page/
    service/
    reports/     # Sub-feature with same structure
      components/
      hooks/
      page/
      service/
```

- **`components/`** — Components used only in this feature. Each component with a CSS file lives in a **named folder** (see [Component folder convention](#component-folder-convention)). Components without CSS stay as flat files.
- **`hooks/`** — Hooks used only in this feature.
- **`page/`** — Page component(s) for the feature. Pages with a CSS file also use a named folder.
- **`service/`** — API or business logic for the feature.

## Infra structure

`infra/` holds **clients** (SDKs, HTTP instance) and **services** (adapters that use those clients, shared across features).

```
infra/
  http.client.ts       # Axios instance, auth, headers
  tanstack.client.ts  # Query client config
  stripe.client.ts    # Stripe SDK instance
  stripe.service.ts   # Adapter: wraps stripe.client, used by features
```

- **`.client.ts`** — Raw client/SDK setup (Stripe, Axios, TanStack Query, etc.).
- **`.service.ts`** — Adapter or shared service that uses a client; e.g. `stripe.service.ts` wraps `stripe.client.ts` and exposes methods used by multiple features.

## Theme & shared UI

- **`theme/theme.ts`** — Theme config (e.g. Mantine or custom).
- **`theme/components/`** — Shared UI (Button, Card, etc.). Each component with CSS uses a named folder (see below).

## Types & validation

- **Feature types:** Put TypeScript interfaces and Zod schemas for a feature in **`<feature-name>.types.ts`** inside that feature folder (e.g. `features/auth/auth.types.ts`, `features/banking/banking.types.ts`). Use Zod for validation; inferred types and interfaces can live in the same file.
- **Global types:** Put app-wide types, namespace declarations, and shared type definitions in a single **`types.ts`** (or `global.types.ts`) at the same level as `features/` (e.g. `src/types.ts`). Use this for things like `declare global`, module augmentation, and types used across multiple features.
- **No types outside type files.** All `type`, `interface`, and `enum` definitions must live in `*.types.ts` (feature-level) or `types.ts` (global) — **never** in services, hooks, utils, or other non-type files. The only exception is **React component props** (`interface FooProps { ... }`), which stay in the component file they belong to.

```text
features/banking/banking.types.ts   # Account, Transaction, accountSchema, etc.
src/types.ts                       # Global types, namespaces, shared enums

# ✅ GOOD — payload types in the feature types file
features/search/search.types.ts    # SearchCriteria, CreateSearchPayload, etc.

# ✅ GOOD — component props stay in the component
features/search/components/SearchCard/SearchCard.tsx   # interface SearchCardProps { ... }

# ❌ BAD — types defined in service or hook files
features/search/service/search.service.ts   # export interface CreateSearchPayload
features/search/hooks/search.hook.ts        # export type SomeType = ...
```

## File naming: `<name>.<use>.ts`

Use the pattern **`<name>.<use>.ts`** (or `.tsx` where applicable) so the file’s role is clear from its name.

| Location | Use suffix | Example |
|----------|------------|--------|
| `utils/` | `.utils` | `date.utils.ts`, `format.utils.ts` |
| `features/<feature>/service/` | `.service` | `banking.service.ts`, `auth.service.ts` |
| `infra/` | `.client`, `.service` | `tanstack.client.ts`, `stripe.client.ts`, `stripe.service.ts` |
| `features/<feature>/` | `.types` | `auth.types.ts`, `banking.types.ts` |

- **Utils:** `utils/date.utils.ts`, `utils/format.utils.ts`
- **Feature types (interfaces + Zod):** `features/auth/auth.types.ts`, `features/banking/banking.types.ts`
- **Global types:** `types.ts` or `global.types.ts` at src root — namespaces, `declare global`, shared types
- **Feature services:** `features/banking/service/banking.service.ts`
- **Infra clients:** `infra/tanstack.client.ts`, `infra/stripe.client.ts`, `infra/http.client.ts`
- **Infra services (adapters):** `infra/stripe.service.ts` — wraps a client, shared across features
- **Errors:** `errors/errors.ts` — custom error classes (e.g. `NotFoundError`, `ValidationError`)

Use the same idea for other types (e.g. `something.hook.ts`, `something.page.tsx`) where it helps.

## Component folder convention

When a component has a co-located CSS file, wrap both files in a **named folder** matching the component name. The `.tsx` file imports its CSS with a **relative** `./` path. Components without CSS stay as flat files in their parent directory.

```text
# ✅ GOOD — component + CSS in a named folder
features/search/components/SearchCard/
  SearchCard.tsx       # imports './SearchCard.css'
  SearchCard.css

theme/components/AppLayout/
  AppLayout.tsx        # imports './AppLayout.css'
  AppLayout.css

features/search/page/DashboardPage/
  DashboardPage.tsx    # imports './DashboardPage.css'
  DashboardPage.css

# ✅ GOOD — component without CSS stays flat
features/search/components/DashboardContent.tsx

# ❌ BAD — .tsx and .css sitting loose together in the parent directory
features/search/components/SearchCard.tsx
features/search/components/SearchCard.css
```

When importing a component from a named folder, use the full path to the file:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
import { SearchCard } from '@/features/search/components/SearchCard/SearchCard'
import { AppLayout } from '@/theme/components/AppLayout/AppLayout'

// ❌ BAD — barrel/index import (no index files)
import { SearchCard } from '@/features/search/components/SearchCard'
```

## Styling rules

- **No inline styles.** Use CSS (or CSS modules) only.
- **One CSS file per component.** For every `ComponentName.tsx` that needs styles, create `ComponentName.css` in the same named folder.
- **Relative CSS imports.** Components import their own CSS with `./ComponentName.css`, not an absolute `@/` path.

```text
# ✅ GOOD
theme/components/AppError/AppError.tsx
theme/components/AppError/AppError.css

# ❌ BAD — inline styles
<button style={{ padding: 8, color: 'blue' }}>Click</button>

# ❌ BAD — absolute path for own CSS
import '@/features/search/components/SearchCard/SearchCard.css'
```
